w different films from around the world 'think' about topics like history, national identity, geopolitics, ethics, gender, genre, affect, religion, surveillance culture, digital aesthetics and the body. Mapping the global diversity of this cinematic thinking, this book greatly expands upon the range of films discussed in Deleuze's Cinema books.Key FeaturesAnalyses several Asian films, including Japan's most famous monster movie Godzilla, the colourful Thai western Tears of the Black Tiger, the South Korean road movie Traces of Love and the Iranian comedy The LizardDiscusses American film noir, recent European art films such as Red Road and The Lives of Others and Hollywood CGI Blockbusters including Hellboy and The Curious Case of Benjamin Button Includes a dedicated chapter on the animated documentary Waltz with BashirStudies host of different directors from Rainer Werner Fassbinder to Baz Luhrmann  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDeleuze, Gilles, -- 1925-1995. 0aMotion pictures -- Philosophy. 0aMotion picturesxPhilosophy. 0aMotion pictures. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh1 aBrown, William, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aBrown, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeamer, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFleming, David H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHadjioannou, Markos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerzog, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJeong, Seung-hoon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin-Jones, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPekerman, Serazer, econtributor.